# CASM WP14 trusted reference: casmmodes
#
# One legal statement per CASM_MODE_* value, so a byte-for-byte comparison
# certifies one opcode per addressing mode. This is the coverage casmemit1 and
# casmhello leave open: between them they only exercise implied, immediate,
# absolute, relative, .BYTE and .WORD.
#
# Hand-assembled from the documented 6502 instruction set, NOT from CASM and NOT
# by reading src/external/casm/opcodes.s -- deriving these bytes from CASM's own
# opcode table would make the comparison circular and could copy a table defect
# into its own reference. (opcodes.s was diffed against these bytes afterwards
# as an independent cross-check, which is a finding if it disagrees, not a
# reason to change this file.)
#
# Source (.ORG $C000) and hand assembly:
#   00 C0        PRG load-address header ($C000, little-endian)
#   E8           INX            ; IMPLIED
#   0A           ASL A          ; ACCUMULATOR
#   A9 01        LDA #$01       ; IMMEDIATE
#   A5 10        LDA $10        ; ZEROPAGE
#   B5 10        LDA $10,X      ; ZEROPAGE_X
#   B6 10        LDX $10,Y      ; ZEROPAGE_Y   (mode exists only for LDX/STX)
#   AD 34 12     LDA $1234      ; ABSOLUTE
#   BD 34 12     LDA $1234,X    ; ABSOLUTE_X
#   B9 34 12     LDA $1234,Y    ; ABSOLUTE_Y
#   6C 34 12     JMP ($1234)    ; INDIRECT
#   A1 10        LDA ($10,X)    ; INDEXED_INDIRECT
#   B1 10        LDA ($10),Y    ; INDIRECT_INDEXED
#   D0 E4        BNE $C000      ; RELATIVE
#
# Relative displacement: the branch sits at $C01A and is 2 bytes, so
# nextPc = $C01C and disp = $C000 - $C01C = -28 = $E4.
#
# Zero-page vs absolute selection is driven by operand width ($10 vs $1234), so
# this fixture also re-exercises the promotion boundary.
#
# bytes: 30
# sha256: c9315d139778f568e44175a2e17479098268d1aea41163db68e93c5ed29c94f0

00 C0
E8
0A
A9 01
A5 10
B5 10
B6 10
AD 34 12
BD 34 12
B9 34 12
6C 34 12
A1 10
B1 10
D0 E4
